From 1d7c7d8bf70c3d2b2abbb5ead3c654978ead419a Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: jillravaliya <jillravaliya@gmail.com>
Date: Wed, 22 Apr 2026 23:37:39 +0530
Subject: [PATCH] kbuild: deb-pkg: propagate hook script failures in builddeb

The 'builddeb' script in the Linux kernel source generates the
maintainer scripts for Debian-based distributions. Currently, it
executes post-installation hooks via run-parts but unconditionally
exits with code 0. This creates a "False Success" vulnerability that
compromises the entire system boot integrity.

THE INVESTIGATION: FROM RING 0 TO THE ROOT OF TRUST
This discovery began when a Ring 0 driver project (developed after
LFD103 using VirtualBox) led to a catastrophic boot failure and
kernel panic on an NVMe-based host system. A deep-dive forensic
analysis (documented at https://github.com/jillravaliya/kernel-panic-investigation/tree/main)
initially targeted the Ubuntu systemd hook
'/usr/lib/kernel/install.d/55-initrd.install', which contains the
following logic flaw (Bug #2141741):

    if [ -e "$INITRD_SRC" ]; then
        ln -fs "$INITRD_SRC" "$KERNEL_INSTALL_STAGING_AREA"
    else
        echo "$INITRD_SRC does not exist, not installing an initrd"
    fi
    exit 0  <-- THE DOWNSTREAM SILENT LIE

In technical dialogue on Launchpad, systemd maintainers (Nick) argued
that while this downstream hook detects the missing initrd, the
"Root of Trust" must be the kernel packaging itself. If the
packaging tool invokes 'run-parts' and it fails, the process must
abort immediately rather than relying on downstream scripts to
guess if a failure occurred.

THE MAINLINE ARCHITECTURAL FLAW:
Following this lead, an audit of the Mainline Kernel source revealed
that the 'builddeb' script (scripts/package/builddeb) mirrors this
exact dangerous behavior in the 'install_maint_scripts' function:

    hookdirs="${hookdirs# }"
    test -n "$hookdirs" && run-parts --arg="${KERNELRELEASE}" \
         --arg="/${installed_image_path}" $hookdirs
    exit 0  <-- THE UPSTREAM SILENT LIE

THE ALPHABETICAL TRAP & NVMe PARADOX:
This upstream exit 0 creates an "Alphabetical Trap." On modular
kernels (CONFIG_BLK_DEV_NVME=m), the storage driver resides
exclusively in the initrd. If an early-sequenced hook, such as a DKMS
build (starting with 'd'), fails, run-parts terminates. Because
builddeb ignores this, the 'initramfs-tools' hook (starting with 'i')
is never reached.

The kernel packaging then "lies" to the package manager with a
successful exit code. GRUB promotes the broken kernel, leading to a
'VFS: unknown-block(0,0)' KERNEL PANIC on reboot because the kernel
cannot see the NVMe drive.

CONCLUSION:
By fixing this Upstream, we ensure the Kernel Build System respects
the integrity of the hook chain. This patch enforces "Defense in
Depth" at the source, preventing unbootable deployments across the
entire Linux ecosystem.

Signed-off-by: jillravaliya <jillravaliya@gmail.com>
Link: https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/systemd/+bug/2141741
---
 scripts/package/builddeb | 7 ++++++-
 1 file changed, 6 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/scripts/package/builddeb b/scripts/package/builddeb
index 3627ca227..6ea768f08 100755
--- a/scripts/package/builddeb
+++ b/scripts/package/builddeb
@@ -98,7 +98,12 @@ install_maint_scripts () {
 			hookdirs="\$hookdirs \$dir/${script}.d"
 		done
 		hookdirs="\${hookdirs# }"
-		test -n "\$hookdirs" && run-parts --arg="${KERNELRELEASE}" --arg="/${installed_image_path}" \$hookdirs
+		if [ -n "\$hookdirs" ]; then
+                    if ! run-parts --arg="\${KERNELRELEASE}" --arg="/\${installed_image_path}" \$hookdirs; then
+                         echo "E: Post-install hooks failed." >&2
+                         exit 1
+                    fi
+                fi
 		exit 0
 		EOF
 		chmod 755 "${pdir}/DEBIAN/${script}"
-- 
